Catrin’ and ‘‘Poppies’ both present separation in the context of a motherchild relationship,
and both explore the powerful and conicted emotions that separation can cause. Clarke’s poem
explores the physical separation that occurred when the speaker gave birth to her daughter,
the ongoing emotional separation caused by her daughter growing up, and her own desire for
separation and independence as a parent. In Weir’s poem, a despondent speaker wrestles with
her emotions after her son has gone off to war. Both poems use language, form and symbolism
to present separation as complex and painful, but while in Clarke’s poem there’s a sense of
desire for separation, the speaker in Weir’s poem desperately tries to hold on to the connection
between her and her son as much as possible.
Clarke and Weir both use vivid language to present the connection between mother and
child, and how this connection is affected by separation. In ‘Catrin’, the speaker describes the
“tight / Red rope of love” that binds her and her daughter together. This “rope” can be seen
to symbolise both the emotional connection between the two and the literal umbilical cord that
unites them. They “Fought over” the rope, which evokes a ‘tug of war’ and emphasises how
their desire to become separate is a struggle because they still have a close, loving bond. This
contrasts with the sewing language used in ‘Poppies’. In the rst stanza, the speaker describes
how she “pinned” a poppy onto her son’s lapel before he left. Describing a close, physical
interaction highlights their connection, but the word “pinned” hints at the pain his departure
causes her. Later, similar language is used to describe the speaker’s nerves as she visits the
war memorial and her stomach makes “tucks”, “darts” and “pleats”. The use of sewing language
hints at a desire to reconnect and ‘stitch’ up the hole that has been left in her life. Both poems
present connections as ‘threads’, highlighting how relationships ‘tie’ people together and how the
separation of these connections is a struggle that can cause discomfort and pain.
